Sidekiq is a separate server/process, just like rails s is for your web app.

Mental model (lock this in)
Thing	Command	Purpose
Rails web server	rails s / puma	Handles HTTP requests
Sidekiq server	bundle exec sidekiq	Runs background jobs

They are independent processes.

How you start Sidekiq
Basic command
bundle exec sidekiq


Thatâ€™s the equivalent of:

rails s


for background jobs.

With options (very common)
bundle exec sidekiq -c 10 -q default -q mailers


-c 10 â†’ 10 threads

-q â†’ queue priority/order

Using config file (production-style)
bundle exec sidekiq -C config/sidekiq.yml


Example sidekiq.yml:

:concurrency: 10
:queues:
  - critical
  - default
  - low

What happens when you run bundle exec sidekiq

Boots Rails environment

Connects to Redis

Registers itself in Redis (processes)

Starts heartbeats

Starts worker threads

Begins fetching jobs

ðŸ‘‰ All without touching rails s

Can Rails app work without Sidekiq running?

âœ… Yes (for web requests)

But:

Background jobs will not execute

Jobs will pile up in Redis

Can Sidekiq run without Rails server?

âœ… Yes

Sidekiq only needs:

Rails codebase

Redis

It doesnâ€™t need rails s running

In production (important)

Usually you run:

multiple web servers

multiple Sidekiq servers

Example:

3 web servers (rails s / puma)
2 sidekiq servers (bundle exec sidekiq)


Totally independent scaling.

Interview-ready one-liner ðŸ”¥

Yes, Sidekiq runs as a separate server process. Just like rails s starts the web server, bundle exec sidekiq starts the Sidekiq worker server to process background jobs.